     <p xml:id="auto_63nn7etb">
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_upizzgj7">
        <m>\textbf{Properties of a Regular Heptagon.}</m>.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_bcfthhz4">
       â™¦ Sum of interior angles = <m> (n-2) \times 180^\circ</m>. Where n is the number of sides.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_a6qqcvxy">
       â™¦ Example for a Heptagon (7-sided polygon).
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_gn408ggi">
        <me>
          (n-2) \times 180^\circ  
        </me>
        <me>
            (7-2) \times 180^\circ = 900^\circ
        </me>      
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_9lq8oxr2">
       â™¦ Sum of exterior angles of any <m>\textbf{polygon(regular or irregular)}</m> is always equl to <m>360^\circ</m> for both regular and irregular polygons.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_mtfrny3n">
        â™¦ Each Interior and Exterior Angle (Regular Polygon Only)
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_sercziiw">
        <me>
        \textbf{Each Interior Angle (for a regular polygon):}    
        </me>
        <me>
            Interior Angle = \frac{(n-2) \times 180^\circ}{n}
        </me>
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Exterior Angle (for a regular polygon):}
        </me>
        <me>
            Exterior Angle = \frac{360^ \circ}{n}
        </me>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_y68tru2m">
       â™¦  Example for a Regular Heptagon:
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_hte6s0kl">
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Interior Angle} = \frac{900}{7}
        </me>
        <me>
            = 128.57^ \circ
        </me>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_7ypera5o">
        <me>
            \textbf{Each Exterior Angle} = \frac{360}{7}
        </me>
        <me>
            =51.43^ \circ
        </me>
    </p><p xml:id="auto_azw4ftgh">
        <m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_cwot2ut0">
        1. What is the sum of all interior angles of a heptagon ?    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_clqmagw4">
        2. How do we calculate the measure of one interior angle of a regular heptagon ?    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_h3cynnam">
       3. Can you find heptagons in real life? 
    </p>
      <example xml:id="auto_su2co55q">
        <statement>
            <sidebyside>
             <p xml:id="auto_loy269gt">
                A regular heptagon  measures 10 cm as indicated in the figure below, find its area given the sum of it's interior angles is<m>\, 900^\circ?</m>
            </p>
             <image>
            <latex-image label="regular-heptagon-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the heptagon
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                        \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/7*\i}:2);
                    }
                    % Draw the heptagon
                    \draw[thick] (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- cycle;
                    \coordinate(0,0);
                    \draw[thick] (P0) --(0,0) node[midway, above left]{10 cm};
                    \draw[thick](0,0) circle(2pt);
                    % Label the vertices
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,...,6} {
                    \node[font=\small] at ({360/7*\i}:2.2) {$P_{\i}$};
                    }
                    <!-- % Mark center point
                    \filldraw[black] (O) circle (2pt) node[above] {\textbf{O}}; -->
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
           </image>
            </sidebyside>
           
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_y2ecej7k">
                There are 7 triangles since a heptagon has 7 sides.
                Area of Triangle <m>P_0OP_1 = \frac{1}{2} ab \, \text{sin }  \, 51.43^\circ </m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nw3qt7xx">
                <md>
                    <mrow>  \triangle P_0OP_1 = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 10\times 10\, \text{ sin} \,51.43^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times \text{ sin } \, 51,43^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times 100\, \text{cm}^2 \times 0.7818 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lz94cit7">
                Therefore the total area 
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp 7 \times 39.0923 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 273.65 \,\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     
    </example>

